{"title":"SwingBot: Learning Physical Features from In-hand Tactile Exploration for Dynamic Swing-up Manipulation","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Robots need to infer object physical properties quickly and without explicit labels to perform dynamic in-hand manipulations; tactile sensors like GelSight provide rich but complex signals, and single exploratory actions capture only partial information.","method":"SwingBot performs two complementary in-hand explorations—tilting (at 20° and 45°) and shaking—using a GelSight sensor. Marker displacement fields (14×12×2) from tilting are encoded by a CNN into a 40-D feature, while a sequence of per-frame CNN features from shaking is aggregated by an LSTM into an 80-D feature; a fusion network concatenates them into a joint physical embedding. The entire pipeline is trained end-to-end in a self-supervised manner by predicting the final swing-up angle, enabling the model to also capture the gel’s own dynamics. Fusing both actions significantly outperforms using either alone or no tactile input (e.g., 10.2°/12.9° error on seen/unseen vs 25.4°/26.8° with no exploration)."},{"problem":"Choosing control parameters for dynamic swing-up on previously unseen objects is challenging because outcomes depend on unobserved physical properties (mass, COM, friction, inertia).","method":"A forward dynamics predictor takes the fused physical embedding and an action parameter (gripper looseness/width at impulse) and outputs the predicted final swing-up angle. At inference, the robot samples candidate gripper widths and executes the one whose predicted angle is closest to the goal, within an impulse–momentum swing-up policy. This self-supervised predictor enables accurate swing-ups on unseen objects, achieving a mean error of 17.2° across targets (45°, 90°, 135°, 180°) and outperforming baselines that lack physical exploration by over 13°."},{"problem":"Learned embeddings should be interpretable and transferable, enabling recovery of explicit physical parameters that drive task dynamics.","method":"With the fusion encoder frozen, a lightweight MLP head regresses mass, center of mass, and moment of inertia, and classifies friction from the learned embedding. Analysis shows complementary strengths of the two explorations on unseen objects—tilting excels at mass and COM (e.g., mass error 0.184 vs 0.263 for shaking), while shaking excels at friction (90.1% vs 75.6% for tilting); the combined embedding balances properties and improves friction to 93.9%. PCA visualizations further show the embedding is task-oriented: objects with similar swing-up policy–angle distributions cluster together, supporting generalization and policy reuse."}]}
